answers.body_markdown:
This is one of the cases where Microsoft contradicts its own rules. If we look at [Create or change a cell reference](https://support.microsoft.com/en-us/office/create-or-change-a-cell-reference-c7b8b95d-c594-4488-947e-c835903cebaa) -&gt; Create a cell reference to another worksheet, we find:

&gt; Note: If the name of the other worksheet contains nonalphabetical
&gt; characters, you must enclose the name (or the path) within single
&gt; quotation marks (&#39;).

But if the worksheet name is `` Excel will *not* enclose the name within single quotation marks (&#39;). Why not? Clearly neither  nor are alphabetical characters, are they?

So Apache POI fails evaluating this, because it relies on the Microsoft rules. See [FormulaParser.java](https://svn.apache.org/viewvc/poi/tags/REL_5_2_3/poi/src/main/java/org/apache/poi/ss/formula/FormulaParser.java?view=markup#l1208) : `// unquoted sheet names must start with underscore or a letter`. 

You can check this using following test:

    ...
      String formula = cell.getCellFormula();
      //formula = formula.replace(&quot;&quot;, &quot;&#39;&#39;&quot;); cell.setCellFormula(formula); //set the sheet name to be a quoted sheet name
      try {
       System.out.println(&quot;Evaluate formula &quot; + formula + &quot; ...&quot;);
       //evaluator.evaluateInCell(cell);
       CellValue cellValue = evaluator.evaluate(cell);
       System.out.println(&quot;Success! Result: &quot;+ cellValue);
      } catch (Exception e) {
       System.out.println(String.format(&quot;Error in the cell: %s, reason: %s&quot;, cell.getAddress(), e.getMessage()));
      }
    ...




If you uncomment the code line:

      //formula = formula.replace(&quot;&quot;, &quot;&#39;&#39;&quot;); cell.setCellFormula(formula); //set the sheet name to be a quoted sheet name

then formula evaluation should work because the sheet name `` is quoted now.

Me tested using current Apache POI version 5.2.3.

_________________________________________________________

The above is the description of the cause of the issue. It is not a solution. It is not even a workaround. To replace unquoted sheet names with quoted ones one would must know all possible affected sheet names. That&#39;s not possible.

The solution would be that Apache POI changes their code in [FormulaParser.java](https://svn.apache.org/viewvc/poi/tags/REL_5_2_3/poi/src/main/java/org/apache/poi/ss/formula/FormulaParser.java). Beginning in [private ParseNode parseSimpleFactor()](https://svn.apache.org/viewvc/poi/tags/REL_5_2_3/poi/src/main/java/org/apache/poi/ss/formula/FormulaParser.java?view=markup#l1526), to [private ParseNode parseRangeExpression()](https://svn.apache.org/viewvc/poi/tags/REL_5_2_3/poi/src/main/java/org/apache/poi/ss/formula/FormulaParser.java?view=markup#l326), up to [ private ParseNode parseRangeable()](https://svn.apache.org/viewvc/poi/tags/REL_5_2_3/poi/src/main/java/org/apache/poi/ss/formula/FormulaParser.java?view=markup#l440). But that would need a reliable rule of what sheet names may be unquoted and what must be quoted. But that rule seems not to exist. So: you don&#39;t have any chance, use it! ;-).

