answers.body_markdown:
From the [document][1] that is an alias for [RequestMapping.params()][2]

&gt;The parameters of the mapped request, narrowing the primary mapping.

&gt;Same format for any environment: a sequence of &quot;myParam=myValue&quot; style expressions, **with a request only mapped if each such parameter is found to have the given value.** Expressions can be negated by using the &quot;!=&quot; operator, as in &quot;myParam!=myValue&quot;. &quot;myParam&quot; style expressions are also supported, **with such parameters having to be present in the request (allowed to have any value).** Finally, &quot;!myParam&quot; style expressions indicate that the specified parameter is not supposed to be present in the request.

For example, let&#39;s say we have method annotated with `GetMappings` and specified with `params`

    @GetMapping(value=&quot;/{id}&quot;, params=&quot;name&quot;)
    public ResponseEntity&lt;List&lt;PersonPayload&gt;&gt; findPerson(@PathVariable Long id, @RequestParam String name){
     ...

    }

Then the `GET` request having `name` as query param will be mapped to the method `findPerson`

    GET - http://localhost:8080/1?name=robert

If the request param `name` is not present then below error will be thrown

    GET - http://localhost:8080/1

    Resolved [org.springframework.web.bind.UnsatisfiedServletRequestParameterException: Parameter conditions &quot;name&quot; not met for actual request parameters:

The value provided in @RequestParam(&quot;name&quot;) is to bind query parameter with `name` value to variable 

    @GetMapping(value=&quot;/{id}&quot;)
    public ResponseEntity&lt;List&lt;PersonPayload&gt;&gt; findPerson(@PathVariable Long id, @RequestParam(&quot;name&quot;) String name){
     ...
    }

One other advantage is we can follow java naming convention for variable incase query parameter having any symbols or `_` 

    @GetMapping(value=&quot;/{id}&quot;)
    public ResponseEntity&lt;List&lt;PersonPayload&gt;&gt; findPerson(@PathVariable Long id, @RequestParam(&quot;first_name&quot;) String firstName){
     ...
    }




  [1]: https://docs.spring.io/spring-framework/docs/5.1.0.RELEASE/javadoc-api/org/springframework/web/bind/annotation/GetMapping.html#params--
  [2]: https://docs.spring.io/spring-framework/docs/5.1.0.RELEASE/javadoc-api/org/springframework/web/bind/annotation/RequestMapping.html#params--

