Your `equals` is broken. You only test if the value is contained in the `List`, not that the three values are equal. I think you wanted

	@Override
	public boolean equals(Object o) {
		Triple t = (Triple) o;
		return triple.get(0).equals(t.triple.get(0))
				&amp;&amp; triple.get(1).equals(t.triple.get(1))
				&amp;&amp; triple.get(2).equals(t.triple.get(2));
	}

Which (obviously) returns `false` with your example data. Also, you can simplify your constructor

	public Triple(int one, int two, int three) {
		this.triple = List.of(one, two, three);
	}

As discussed in the comments, and pointed out in other answers; your original issues were caused by a hashcode based on simple addition where all three values had the same sum. And your equals was broken because `a` could equal `b` without `b` equaling `a` (since `a` might contain one value that is present in `b`, while `b` might contain three values with only one of them present in `a`). It would probably be best to store the three values as `int` fields. You should also make the `Triple` immutable, since changing any field would alter the instance&#39;s hashcode. You might as well override `toString` and make it `Comparable` while you are at it. So the final version might look something like,

	class Triple implements Comparable&lt;Triple&gt; {
		private final int a, b, c;

		public Triple(int one, int two, int three) {
			this.a = one;
			this.b = two;
			this.c = three;
		}

		@Override
		public int hashCode() {
			return java.util.Objects.hash(this.a, this.b, this.c);
		}

		@Override
		public boolean equals(Object o) {
			if (o instanceof Triple) {
				Triple that = (Triple) o;
				return this.a == that.a 
						&amp;&amp; this.b == that.b 
						&amp;&amp; this.c == that.c;
			}
			return false;
		}

		@Override
		public String toString() {
			return String.format(&quot;(%d, %d, %d)&quot;, a, b, c);
		}

		@Override
		public int compareTo(Triple that) {
			int comp = Integer.compare(this.a, that.a);
			if (comp != 0) {
				return comp;
			}
			comp = Integer.compare(this.b, that.b);
			if (comp != 0) {
				return comp;
			}
			return Integer.compare(this.c, that.c);
		}
	}

For two lists to compare equally, each list must have the `same size` and `list1.get(i).equals(list2.get(i))` must be `true` for `0 &lt;= i &lt; List.size()`

This is easily achieved by the following:
- use the pattern matching `instanceof` (Java 16+) which casts and assigns `obj` to `t` if true.
- simply compare the lists using equals since lists override equals using the afore mentioned one-to-one comparisons.
```
public boolean equals(Object obj) {
    if (obj instanceof Triple t) {
        return t.triple.equals(this.triple);
    }
    return false;
}
```
Also, you can create the `hashCode` as follows.
```
public int hashCode() {
        return Objects.hash(triple.get(0), triple.get(1), triple.get(2));
}

&gt; boolean b = answersSet.contains(triple2); //returns true

It does, because both your `equals` method, as well as your `hashCode()` method, produce identical values here. At first glance, it doesn&#39;t look like it. But, really, this is what your code does. Let&#39;s go through it:

## hashCode

&gt; return triple.get(0).hashCode() + triple.get(1).hashCode() + triple.get(2).hashCode();

The hashCode of an `Integer` value is simply.. itself. Thus, for `-4,0,4`, you end up with a hashCode of __0__. After all, -4 + 0 + +4 is 0.

The hashcode of the `0, 0, 0` is also __0__.

This is called a hash collision. It doesn&#39;t mean your implementation of `hashCode()` is definitely broken; it happens. By simple pigeon hole principle: There are 2^32 different possible hashcodes, and there are 2^96 different `Triple` instances; therefore, it __has__ to be the case that at least 2^64 different `Triple` instances nevertheless have the same hashCode.

__This is fine__ - nothing in the spec requires that different objects have different hashcodes. The spec dictates only two things:

* If 2 objects are equal they __must__ have the same hashCode (your code does that right).
* If lots of different objects nevertheless hash to the same hashcode, the performance of hashset and hashmap and friends will be really bad. It&#39;ll work, though. Just, not very fast. This is called &#39;hash distribution&#39;.

Your hash distribution is mostly fine. You could do a better job by taking the position of your numbers into account. Something like:

```
@Override public int hashCode() {
  return triple.get(0) + triple.get(1) * 31 + triple.get(2) * 97;
```

31 and 97 are prime numbers. That&#39;s intentional.

## equals

Your equals method is broken. It doesn&#39;t concern itself with order! It says that equality implies that the provided `Triple` object contains every value of `this` triple.

Given that `this` triple is 0/0/0, your checks if the `triple` passed in contains 0 (it does). Then it checks if it contains 0 (it.. still does), and then checks it a third time, which.. it still does.

This is really, really broken. It clashes with hashCode (0/0/0 and 5/0/4 are equal, but do not have the same hashCode, that&#39;s a violation), and is a bizarre definition of equality. It also isn&#39;t reversible, and equals methods have to be: if `a.equals(b)` is true, then `b.equals(a)` must also be true, but with 0/0/0 and -4/0/4 this isn&#39;t true either.

Separately, your equals method will throw a `ClassCastException` if you pass a non-triple to it, which is also broken. The documentation of equals describes what you have to do. You broke 3 of its rules.

Let&#39;s fix all of them:

The fix is to check each _position_:

```
@Override public  boolean equals(Object other) {
  if (other == null || other.getClass() != Triple.class) return false;
  Triple t = (Triple) other;
  return t.triple.get(0).equals(this.triple.get(0)) &amp;&amp;
    t.triple.get(1).equals(this.triple.get(1)) &amp;&amp;
    t.triple.get(2).equals(this.triple.get(2));
}
```

## or..

use records, or, [lombok&#39;s `@Value`](https://projectlombok.org/features/Value) which takes care of all this for you:

```
public record Triple(int a, int b, int c) {}
```

or

```
@Value
public class Triple {
  List&lt;Integer&gt; triple;

  public Triple(int a, b, c) {
    this.triple = List.of(a, b, c);
  }
}
```

More generally it feels like this class should have 3 `int` typed fields instead of one `List&lt;Integer&gt;` typed one.

